- ğŸ§  Problem / Business Scenario: You are a logistics analyst at an online retail company.
Your operations team wants to monitor how long it takes, on average, for orders to be fulfilled after theyâ€™re placed.
Theyâ€™ve asked you to calculate the average fulfillment time in days between when an order was placed and when it was fulfilled.

- ğŸ“š Concepts: DATE_DIFF + AVG

- ğŸ’¡ Why this matters: 
  - Faster fulfillment leads to happier customers and fewer support complaints.
  - Enables comparisons across weeks, months, or different fulfillment centers.
  - Identifies trends or bottlenecks in shipping and warehouse processes.

-- ğŸ”„ 1. Drop existing table to avoid conflicts

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS users;
DROP TABLE IF EXISTS purchases;

-- ğŸ§± 2. Create the table schema

CREATE TABLE orders (
  order_id INT,
  order_date DATE,
  fulfill_date DATE
);

-- ğŸ“Š 3. Insert sample/mock data

INSERT INTO orders VALUES
(1, '2024-01-01', '2024-01-03'),
(2, '2024-01-05', '2024-01-10'),
(3, '2024-01-10', '2024-01-15');

-- ğŸ” 4. Final query

SELECT 
AVG(fulfill_date - order_date) AS avg_fulfillment_days
FROM orders;

